Chop your @sweet potato{1} into 1cm thick wedges (no need to peel). Pop onto a lined #baking tray{} and drizzle with oil. Season with @salt{} and @pepper{}. Give your #baking tray{} a shake to coat evenly then spread out and roast until soft and golden, ~{15-17%minutes}. Turn halfway through cooking.

Meanwhile, drain and reserve the juice from the @pineapple rings{1/2}. Chop into small chunks. Thinly slice the @red chilli{1/2} (remove the seeds if you're not a fan of heat). Roughly chop the @coriander{1/2}(roughly chopped) (stalks and all). Chop the @broccoli{1} into small florets.

Heat a splash of oil in a #frying pan{} over medium-high heat. When hot, lay in the @gammon steaks{2}. Brown for ~{1%minute} on each side. Reduce the heat to medium and cook for a further ~{3-4%mins} on each side.

> IMPORTANT: The gammon needs to be cooked all the way through before eating.

While the gammon is cooking, mix the pineapple chunks with half the chilli and the coriander in a #small bowl{}. Grate in the zest of the @lime{1/2} and season with salt and pepper. Mix in a glug of olive oil and the juice from the pineapple chunks. Taste and add a pinch of sugar (if you have some) and a squeeze of lime juice if it needs it.

> Be careful not to use all the pineapple juice - only add a glug.

Once the gammon is cooked, transfer to a #plate{} and cover with foil to keep warm. Wash out the #frying pan{}, return to medium-high heat and add a splash of oil. Add the broccoli and remaining chilli. Stir-fry until tender, ~{4-5%minutes}.

When the wedges are ready, share between your plates and serve the gammon alongside. Add any resting juices from the gammon to the salsa and spoon this over the gammon. Serve the broccoli alongside. ENJOY!